ized": false, "mention": "aquatic", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5487439632415771, "span": {"begin": 2290, "end": 2297}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "seagrasses", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7783815860748291, "span": {"begin": 2309, "end": 2319}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4716"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "PSII", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9552921652793884, "span": {"begin": 2335, "end": 2339}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4716"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "PSII", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8378168940544128, "span": {"begin": 2388, "end": 2392}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4716"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "PSII", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9740762114524841, "span": {"begin": 2439, "end": 2443}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "QB", "obj": "DNA", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2550, "end": 2552}}], "text": "The empirical support of this KER is considered high.  Rationale:&nbsp;A large body of experimental evidence demonstrates strong incidence, dose, and temporal concordance between chemical binding or interference at the QB site of the D1 protein and reduced Photosystem II (PSII) efficiency across cyanobacteria, algae, aquatic plants, and higher plants. These effects are consistently observed for well-characterized PSII inhibitors, with relatively few inconsistencies.  Evidence:  Dose concordance:&nbsp;In isolated pea thylakoid membranes, QB site herbicides with higher inferred QB affinity (diuron, terbuthylazine, metribuzin) inhibited PSII electron transfer and fluorescence-based PSII performance at substantially lower concentrations than lower-affinity inhibitors (e.g., bentazon, metobromuron). Reported I50 values were around 7&ndash;8 &times; 10&minus;8M for diuron and 1&ndash;2 &times; 10&minus;7&nbsp;M for terbuthylazine/metribuzin, derived from both DPIP photoreduction (PSII activity) and OJIP fluorescence (1&ndash;Vj, reflecting QA reduction and QB site interference)&nbsp;(Battaglino, Grinzato and Pagliano, 2021).&nbsp;  Incidence concordance: Direct inhibition of plastoquinone binding at the QB&nbsp;site leads to accumulation of reduced QA and impaired QA to QB&nbsp;electron transfer, which is consistently associated with reduced PSII efficiency in functional assays, including fluorescence-based measurements (Vermaas et al., 1984; Sundby et al., 1993; Broser et al., 2011).  Structural&ndash;functional concordance: Crystallographic and molecular studies have shown that PSII inhibitors bind within the QB_BB pocket of the D1 protein, physically blocking plastoquinone exchange. This structural interference provides direct mechanistic evidence linking QB_BB binding to impaired PSII electron transport and decreased PSII efficiency (Broser et al., 2011; Zimmermann et al., 2006).  Genetic concordance: Mutations in the D1 protein affecting the QB_BB region alter herbicide binding and are accompanied by changes in PSII electron transport efficiency and photochemical performance, supporting a causal relationship between perturbation at the QB_BB site and decreased PSII efficiency (Ohad and Hirschberg, 1992; Sundby et al., 1993).  Temporal concordance: In aquatic plants and seagrasses, inhibition of PSII efficiency occurs rapidly following exposure to PSII herbicides, while partial or full recovery of PSII function is observed after removal of the stressor, consistent with a direct and reversible inhibition of QB_BB-mediated electron transport (Macinnis-Ng and Ralph, 2003; Wilkinson et al., 2015).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:17:21 +0000 2026"}